Editor, sugar maple

It's urgent

The uneasy feeling was creeping up on me.

On January 23rd, when the news of the "closure" came from Wuhan, Liu Jun was not too worried. A week ago, returning from his job in Guangzhou to his hometown in Xiaogan, Hubei Province, he saw very few people wearing masks on the road. It seemed to happen overnight. He didn't digest all the incoming messages so quickly. "I'm not from Wuhan, " he said. "Let's wait and see. He told people that according to his plan, he would return to Guangdong on the eighth day of the Lunar New Year. He brought two more days'medicine, so he could eat till the tenth day.

Three drugs, to be exact. As an hiv-infected person, Liu Jun needs daily medication to suppress the virus in his body. There are eight drugs available free of charge in the country, and doctors typically choose three of them as treatment options for each individual. Triple."That's what they all say. Once every three months, the infected person will go to the designated hospital to pick up the medicine.

It all happened so fast. Following the announcement of the shutdown in Wuhan, a number of other cities followed in Hubei Province on the same day. By the morning of January 24,13 cities in the province, including Ezhou, Huanggang and Xiaogan, had been closed down one after another. There's no way out. He panicked. Unlike food or face masks, AIDS drugs are not available on the market. Not just any hospital can take medicine, according to the principle of territorial management, only in the location of the relationship between the hospital to take medicine. Shanghai accepts only local residents, while Wuhan allows only those with residence permits and local student cards. Such targeted drug provisions in the patient community has long been opposed, but difficult to shake, after all, free AIDS treatment involves local financial expenditure.

The unprecedented closure of the city has helped to contain the spread of the epidemic, but has also caused some confusion, with drug withdrawal among the AIDS infected population being one of the secondary problems.

But for the individual, it was a disaster. There are serious consequences to going off your meds. AIDS treatment requires a high degree of compliance, daily medication to suppress the virus number-minutes time card, many infected people set three or four alarm clocks. Once the drug stopped, the virus rebound, may lead to disease, but also the body will develop resistance. Once the anti-aids system to provide free medicine is no longer effective, you need to change the sky-high price of self-financed medicine, or even no cure.

By the end of October 2018, Hubei Province had reported 19,166 cases of HIV infection and disease, the 13th highest number of cases in the country, and the same troubles affected people who were not included in the statistics. Wang Shulin, a native of Hubei Province, studied in the United States and came from a well-off family. He had never used free Chinese medicine. On January 24, he will fly back to the United States from Wuhan, a city in Hubei that was still under siege. After the city was closed, he immediately bought a new ticket and flew from Guangzhou instead. He needs to solve is the domestic this journey, a city fly to Guangzhou ticket sold out, so he bought years later first to Nanjing, then change to Guangzhou ticket. After much ado about nothing, he felt at ease. On the evening of the New Year's Eve, while he was packing, all flights from a city airport were cancelled. He can't go to America, he can't go to Guangzhou, he can't go anywhere.

Like ripples on the surface of the lake, the blockade began in Wuhan and was extended to all counties and cities in Hubei Province, and soon reached the village level. Li Jing of Jingzhou found that the only road from his village to the outside world was blocked by a small car, leaving only a gap, "it can take a person, or ride a motorcycle or something like that. ". No personnel or vehicles are allowed to pass without special circumstances. The village where Liu Quan lived in Tianmen was more thorough, and all the intersections were covered with dirt and blocked so tightly that even ambulances and supply trucks could not get in. Fengcun to the general people can indeed bring a sense of security, but to the face of drug AIDS infected people brought great fear.

If their sphere of activity is still within the village, those from outside the province who work in Hubei will find themselves under severe confinement when they return home. He and his family have been quarantined at home as high-risk victims since he returned to rural Hebei years ago. He felt that the villagers were reasonable to him, and that the Party secretary and the community doctor had only repeatedly stressed to him that he should pay attention to his temperature, and there was no resentment or hostility.

He Wangsheng calculated that the drug could last until the end of the 14-day isolation period, he was slightly relieved. He said to the village Party secretary, "I will certainly cooperate, and I will do a real self-isolation in all aspects. ". But when it's over, will I be free? "

"I can't give you a definite answer on that. "

Privacy

From the first day of taking the drug, a concern has been deeply embedded in the minds of people infected with HIV. In the words of Wang Yadong, a Wuhan native, "If there is an earthquake or a war, can we still take medicine? "? "every three months you go to the hospital, they give you three-month pills for life, which means that every three months, the clock starts ticking again. Several interviewees told people that the fear of going off the drugs was far greater than the fear of knowing the infection.

Where does Wang Yadong go? He always takes medicine with him. He hid hundreds of pills deep in his schoolbag and locked them in his locker when he got home. In addition to the three-month supply prescribed by his doctor, he bought an extra month from his own source as a reserve. And finally, he had a little metal bottle on his key chain with three days'worth of medicine in it, and he was afraid to leave his bag behind. He often travels on business. He always keeps his medicine in two separate boxes. "If one box is missing, the other box can be salvaged. ". "

Carrying enough medicine around is a deep-rooted common sense, but it conflicts with going home for the Spring Festival. Few people tell their families about the infection, and too many pills and bottles can easily be found, arouse suspicion. The choice of those who return home is almost the same, the estimated number of days, with a few more days, the rest stay in the usual place.

All the chronic patients who need to take medicine for a long time will face the crisis of drug withdrawal when the city closes down the village. People living with HIV are in a much tougher position than other chronic diseases, and they need to keep it a secret while they search for drugs. Isolated at home in Hebei, when the village Party secretary said that any difficulties can be put forward to help solve the time, he wangsheng only one idea, can not say, would rather break the drug can not say.

In front of unsuspecting family members, they need to cover up their panic. On New Year's Eve, after receiving the news that Xiaogan had sealed off the city, Liu Jun turned to his mother and calmly asked whether he would have dumplings or Rice for dinner. The question had been answered by the time it had been asked, and he was not listening to his mother.

All of people's phone interviews have been extremely difficult. Many declined to be interviewed for fear of a breach of privacy. Some of those willing to be interviewed can only type, not speak, because they are with their families. The man who studied in the United States, avoiding his parents, went to his brother's house to answer the phone -- as if he were the only one in the family who knew him. Liu has at home and "people" telephone, carefully choose the wording, will all the family may arouse suspicion of sensitive statements, including processing. Liu Jun has two wechat accounts, two mobile phones, and carries around with him only one that deals with AIDS treatment.

Asked about the consequences of identity leaks, a gay HIV infected person to "people" reporter three times said "can not imagine. "You are this (comrade) identity, in the ordinary countryside is already the treason, if you because of this identity and illness of the situation to say out again, it is really no place for you. "

In today's medical conditions, AIDS infected with the external characteristics of ordinary people are no different. Under normal circumstances, this area of privacy can be preserved if one is careful. No one would store a drug in its original bottle, just rip the label off and bottle it again. Wang bought three black bottles so that the shape and color of the tablets could not be seen from the outside.

Once at the airport, the security officer saw his medication during an x ray and asked what it was. I have a heart condition. It's a heart condition drug. It was a set of responses that had been prepared and rehearsed, and to that end he had looked up which drugs could not be missed. He needs to take his medicine after lunch. At work, his alarm clock will go off on time. The problem was also solved early. He had been "instilling in his colleagues" the idea that heart-disease drugs were part of the high-blood-pressure category, and because high-blood-pressure drugs needed to be taken on time, he set an alarm.

Xie Xiaojian, a college student in Jiangsu Province, takes his medicine at night, and though roommate never asks about his alarm clock, a set of words has already been thought out, saying he has a bad stomach. He sleeps in the top bunk, he's inconspicuous, and he slips pills into his mouth while his roommates play video games.

As a gay man, Xie knows that admitting HIV infection is more difficult to talk about than coming out. They did not create this situation, but the social climate forced them to choose this way. He came out to his family and was accepted, and roommate, who had a history of homophobia, was kind to him when he learned of his sexuality. "I can't imagine what they would think of me if they knew I was HIV positive, if they would kick me out of this dorm. "

Neither his school nor his hometown is in Hubei, and he has enough medicine to last a month, but on the evening of the first day of the Lunar New Year, when news spread online that people infected with HIV had stopped taking their medicine, he cried. He remembered a friend who had died because of a delay in taking his medication. He began to retweet messages over and over again on Weibo, sending private messages to Big v's to help forward them. But he soon discovered that the information was being curbed and that he was reading far less than normal.

"from the infection to the present experience, because of my own knowledge of the disease, I did not feel that the sky was falling, and I felt that I was completely able to handle it on my own, completely able to cope. In a phone interview with people, Xie choked up again. "It wasn't until this incident that I realized that in such a sudden situation, the needs of marginalized groups like us could easily be ignored, never felt so vulnerable in our community. "

Tianmen AIDS patient Liu Quan has a college degree in transmission, and he considered sending a request for help on the Internet. But when he saw the netizen "Zou junxi makeup artist" after the encounter, to cancel the idea. That person and his situation is almost the same, is also Tianmen people, in Weibo for help, the police came to verify, the infection was known to his family, he also encountered a large number of online violence, and finally cleaned up and deleted Weibo.

Liu Quan can do things, is to call at home, again and again to Tianmen city CDC call. No answer. Only later did he learn that the entire department of AIDS prevention was almost transferred to deal with the pneumonia epidemic. "people" according to a number of channels to understand, Hubei CDC situation is generally the same.

Workarounds

Wuhan City closure that day began, Huang Haojie has been receiving AIDS drug withdrawal for help, every day dozens. He knew that his Spring Festival holiday had ended early. As the head of the Wuhan Gay Center, he maintains daily contact with the staff of the AIDS Prevention Office of the Hubei Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention.

In fact, after the city closed, the provincial center for Disease Control and Prevention was also aware of the problem, quickly introduced alternative measures, requiring the province's treatment points to allow people living with AIDS in other places to fill out a drug application, can get drugs. But in Hubei Province, where it is difficult to reach people outside the province, the provincial centers for Disease Control and prevention created a working contact letter template for those who are quarantined outside the province, asking them to get an attending doctor to sign it and seek help at a treatment site outside the province.

The measures were posted within the Wechat Group of provincial disease control officials and could not reach the infected community directly. Huang Haojie will continue to sum up these news updates published on the public sign. Seven staff members and two volunteers returned to work on the first day of the Lunar New Year. They work from home, scattered all over the place, starting at 10 a.m. with case consultations and working until after 11 p.m. every day.

Wong issued a call on Wechat, headlined: "Urgent Appeal for help. The lives and deaths of these people should not be forgotten. ". This time he seems to have gone a little too far, and may have struck a nerve.

Unlike the gay community with social needs, and with its secretive medical records, the community of people living with HIV is much more loosely connected. Especially in the old home, many people are completely cut off with nearby patients. "I'm just familiar with the city I live in. I'm not familiar with my hometown. How can I find it? I'm at a loss. "said Liu Jun.. Like him, many people rely on the Internet search, see the news issued by the Wuhan Gay Center, before they know the steps of drug withdrawal in different places.

AIDS treatment drugs as prescription drugs, before the release of patients to confirm the identity is necessary. Huang told people that a large number of people infected with HIV had been exposed to blackmail and threats. Since then, China's disease control and prevention authorities have adjusted their information management authority for AIDS patients to protect their privacy, it's unreachable from anywhere else.

In the process of implementing the new regulations, some deformation has also occurred. For example, what was meant to be a work contact letter to address the problem of drug collection by infected people stranded outside the province became an equally necessary document for drug collection in some urban areas of Hubei Province. In some cases, additional requirements have been added, such as confirmation reports. But the new rules do solve a number of problems. Wang Shulin, who studied in the United States and has never received free drugs in China, got the medicine in a certain city.

And there are a lot of people who are stuck. Xiaogan Liu Jun card in the work contact letter. Before the new rules were implemented, the local CDC responded that he needed to be identified by a call from a CDC staff member or a doctor in charge in Guangzhou, where he was being treated. He has called A city-level and two district-level prevention and control agencies in Guangzhou, not a connection.

After the new rules were introduced, the bar for Liu Jun to get his medicine became even higher. Before, all he had to do was find the doctor in charge and make a phone call. Now, not only did he have to find him, but he also had to sign a sealed work contact letter.

He's just trying to prove you're who you say you are. It's a simple matter. There's a lot of ways to do it. Registration records, hospital electronic reports, with names on them. It doesn't have to be this complicated. Who in their right mind would take this. "

In a village in Hebei Province, he told himself to follow the process and try not to think about the final problem until he could walk through the door -- as if not only he but his family couldn't get out of the house. He did manage to get a job offer from Hubei. But then he realized he couldn't go any further. The local CDC can't get through.

Even if the final step of the people, may also be like the Hubei Wu point of the two infected people, was told by the hospital shortage of medicine, to give priority to local supply. What they need is a trial version of the COVID-19, which states that it can be used as an antiviral treatment for COVID-19. AIDS treatment drugs by the provincial CDC unified distribution to all cities, itself is limited supply. Kleenex is a second-line drug in the free drugs, first-line drugs do not work only need to use, use the population is limited, less reserves.

On January 26, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention issued a notice on guaranteeing free antiretroviral drugs for people living with HIV in other places. Huang Haojie was slightly pleased, "because there are national prefix units, since the document issued down, with a certain degree of mandatory. ". But he also worries that, as with the Hubei Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention, "there is still a lot of uncertainty about how it will be implemented and how it will be communicated down there. He knew that many people would not be able to get their medicine and would need to return to the community to seek help.

The community saves itself

Civil Society is moving quickly. Drug support groups have been set up, patients with express delivery or with the city to borrow drugs, to save the face of drug withdrawal imminent. Outside the official channels, drugs circulate.

As early as 2018, in order to solve the problem of temporary medical shortage of out-of-home patients, "HIV squirrel" placed the "first aid kit" in many large and medium-sized cities throughout the country, and entrusted it to a trusted patient for safekeeping, whom he called "The Guardian" . This time, many patients and "Guardians" who had been assisted by him were called to be helpers. Li Hui, a doctor in Qingdao, Shandong Province, has launched a charity organization called "Jie Long" , with 20 organizations from Chongqing, Xinjiang, Guangxi, Shenzhen and other parts of the country joining the campaign to announce how to ask for help.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Free Medicine First Aid Kit

The center has also set up a drug support group. In this group of more than 50 people, everyone except the staff changed the intra-group designation. "liaoning-shufatai" means that a person is in Liaoning, and the drug that can be loaned is Shufatai; "wuhan-yifei" means a person is in Wuhan, and can be loaned by Wellen; "Ezhou-tiira" means a person is in Ezhou, tenofovir, Wellen, and Lamivudine are among the most common combinations on loan.

On Jan. 26, Hubei's delivery system was found to be nearly disabled after the foundation approved reimbursement for the cost of delivery of medicines borrowed from patients at the Wuhan Center. Made a number of phone calls, even if the customer service desk said it can send, no one went to work in the network. The success of the package does not mean that it can be delivered, "these deliveries have been piling up at our stations for days. Our cars can't leave Wuchang. As time went on, the situation got worse and worse. Before, EMS could still send the mail. On the night of January 26, the road was also blocked. All outlets in Wuhan were closed, and it was even more impossible to reach the lower counties and cities. SF express can fly it, but they don't send drugs.

In this case, the tables have turned. The situation seemed to be the most severe as he was trapped in his home in the countryside of Hebei Province, but he was rescued earlier. As the logistics were not blocked, a patient in Henan sent him medicine is already on the way.

On the other hand, the center has set up a "Love Caravan" to transport people infected with HIV to and from hospitals in Wuhan. All of them stopped on New Year's Eve. By the second day of the New Year, the taxi was also requisitioned by the government. With three or four cars assigned to each community and limited transport capacity, even the need to transport medical staff was only partially met, so teams of volunteers sprang up in all districts of Wuhan. Huang did not ask for their help, "a very important reason is that others may not be willing to send aids such a community. ". "Team Love" is full of gay people or people with AIDS.

The problem of cars was solved, but the problem of road closures in the city was insoluble. It's hard to tell what information you can trust. News that the Hankou, Wuchang and Hanyang districts would block each other spread early this morning, and tencent's real-time rumor-dispelling platform refuted the rumor. But as you drive down the road, the blockade is becoming a reality. On January 27, Wang Jianguo, the driver of the convoy, encountered only one blockade of the Panlongcheng bridge during the day. The bridge was later lifted, but by January 29, all the bridges from Hankou to Panlong City are blocked.

To get through the checkpoint, sometimes it takes a bit of luck to just monitor your temperature and let you through. Sometimes required a few lies, he would say that the people sitting on the car is a chronic disease patients, AIDS infected with the identity of the bottle. Some of the card points open one side on the release, some card points regardless of who is on the car, just to see if there is a pass.

Cross-district transport is no longer possible unless a civil service or medical personnel pass is in hand. But even if you set up a perimeter, it's still blocked from time to time. Sometimes it's a main road, sometimes it's between the second and third ring roads. The once-handy mobile navigation is disabled. Change happens all the time, and depending on what's going on in the group, it's not accurate. Once, after receiving an infected person who had taken the medicine, Wang Jianguo found that he could not go back the way he had come. He had to shelve the infected person to another residence in the city.

Technically, it's against the law for him to drive on the road. Wuhan has imposed a ban on all motor vehicles, with the exception of certain vehicles, since January 26. Violators will be severely punished until 12 points are scored. However, according to the control and Prevention Headquarters, "forbidden vehicles are informed 24 hours in advance by SMS, and vehicles that have not been informed by SMS are allowed to pass. ". In addition to being the driver of the "Love Convoy" , Wang Jianguo is also part of the volunteer convoy that ferries medical staff. No one from either convoy has received a text.

At the end of January, his volunteer convoy of medical workers was suspended. The coordinator put out a call in the group, and someone's already had 12 points deducted. "there is no way for us to be self-assured in our charitable work. We will decide whether we should continue to do voluntary work after reviewing the follow-up policies. "He said.

The final step

With the passage of time, the situation of drug withdrawal in urban areas has been largely resolved. Liu Jun couldn't get through to Guangzhou. But with the help of the Wuhan Center, his personal information was confirmed by the provincial center for Disease Control and Prevention. He got the medicine on his electric bike.

The situation in the villages of Hubei Province is quite different. Public Welfare Organizations can help all help, but express can not reach, the village was closed, the nearby can not find people who can borrow medicine. With the proper paperwork in place, at the last step of the extraction process, everyone had to go back to fighting their own battles.

Liu Quanyou of Tianmen found himself in an awkward situation. His village is on the border of two places. His road seems to be more than others, not only can go to a county, you can go to heaven. Hospitals in both places are promising to give him drugs.

But none of it works. There's no public transportation, and some of the inmates did get their meds on a three-hour walk. He checked the map. He was more than 100 kilometers away from the drug point at Tianmen. It was a nine-hour walk, and he left work early in the morning, even if he had to rule out getting lost in unfamiliar places and getting stopped on the way. Not to mention, how do you explain that to a family that doesn't even know you're gone.

It is only 6 kilometers away from the pharmacy in county a, separated by a river. The ferry's stopped. There's a roadblock on the river bridge. As early as the first day of the year he knew it would not work, his uncle wanted to cross the bridge to visit relatives, was stopped back. Because it's cross-borough, you need a pass.

He did not give up, holding the attitude of trying to cross the river bridge. This trip, it's a risk. He lied to his family about visiting an aunt in the next village. In fact, as soon as the two sides asked, the lie was punctured, he thought, if asked again, said the road met the old classmate.

Walk to the bridge, and the conversation will end in a few rounds. "I'm going to the hospital. " "what's the matter with you? " "my family is sick. " "no, no. "He dared not pursue it any further.

He calls the CDC in county a again and asks for a home delivery. "It's not practical. Two hundred people like this need service. I can't go door-to-door and give it to you. "

Examples like Liu Quan's are common in rural Hubei Province. Li Jing of Jingzhou was one of the lucky ones. He told people that he was able to get the drugs because a few conditions were met. The closure of the village is not too strict, no digging ditches, no filling, there are supplies to and from vehicles. His neighbor, a village official, was on the bus and could help. He just told him, "there's something urgent in the county seat. ". He has a relative in the county who can pick up the medicine and give it to the village official.

In the midst of the tough situation facing the countryside, discussions are under way among staff at the Wuhan Center. They came up with the ultimate solution, called the police, asked the police to drive to the hospital. How do you explain that to the police, when you start talking about it, you can say you have depression, you can say you have diabetes. To this end, they also looked up relevant information, prepared a set of words, "young diabetes complications quickly, to tell him some more serious data. ".

There are people who have been infected with it, and they've managed to get it. But Liu Quan has very repulsive to this ultimate solution, "this reason feels like a bit far-fetched. ". What if he thinks I'm making it up, and he doesn't want to make it worse. "

On the fourth day of the year, an even worse situation occurred. There was a confirmed case in the village, a vegetable farmer selling vegetables in Wuhan. It's harder to make excuses to get out of the house. I was fidgeting. I was losing my mind. "Liu Quan said to the character.

The clock is ticking. The medicine's only four days away. Finally, he did what he thought he was too scared to do. He called the police.

Run the barrier

He did not conceal the identity of AIDS patients, in addition to personal information, on the phone, Liu has to tell his truth.

That phone call was just the beginning. He went into a complicated maze. 110 suggested that he contact the quarantine command center, which told him to go to the Transportation Department. The Department of Transportation can't get through. He's called back to 110. 110. Tell him to call the police station. Find the police station, the other side told him, pass is necessary, let him contact the hospital. Round and round, hard to find the health center phone, the other side told him, can issue a pass, but only in Tianmen, can not go to a county. He goes to 110 again, the other side attitude is still very good, again after internal feedback, answer him finally, sorry, really can not help.

He also called Tianmen Petition Bureau, the other side said he can open a certificate to let him go to a county, but need him to bring a copy of identity card, the original is not allowed, "where can not copy. ". Which means he'll have to find a copy shop first. This is the village. Where can I get a copy? "

When he looked at the location of the Bureau of letters and visits, he could not laugh or cry, to go there, and to go to Tianmen City hospital almost the distance.

He again to Tianmen and a county CDC made a round of calls, in the hope that can be entrusted to get, the other side said, must be present, draw blood to confirm.

He spent two days on the phone, and every time he called, he had to go over the In & Out, and every time he called, he was risking a lot of privacy. Eventually, he found himself back where he started.

Lau found something. There's nothing he can do. He could not rush through the gate without a plan, and play it by ear, for the mere act of going out "required a long search for opportunity, and a great many reasons. ". If it fails, "there's a high risk of discovery. ".

It's too hard. There's not a single agency that can help me. Even though I'm only six kilometers away from the CDC, I'm living in a world of hurt. "He said.

Just waiting to go off. Two days.

By the end of January, the center had received nearly 500 requests for help for drug withdrawal, 80 percent of which had found a solution, and the unfinished ones were the most difficult. In one case, the person was quarantined with a fever and "had no way to get the medicine unless he had a showdown with his parents. ". "

On Jan. 31, the Wuhan Gay and Lesbian Center published an article titled, What to do if medication is interrupted due to current force majeure factors. Huang Haojie did not forward the first time, but dragged a few days, his heart does not want to send it out, how much will pass on the pessimistic mood. But it was a choice I had to make.

People who seem to be far away from the drug-withdrawal crisis suddenly start to panic. The Jiangsu University student, Xie Xiaojian, borrowed his medicine. He assured the other that he didn't have to worry about him, he had enough medicine. But soon he saw the news that all the passenger trains in his hometown had been suspended indefinitely. The outbreak in his area was not serious, and he had been told that he would start work on February 3. He could not have foreseen the changes. Now, he can't get back to the pharmacy, and there's less than 10 days left. To his dismay, it took three days for the shipment to reach the provincial capital, Nanjing. The Guy He's helping, he's going off his meds. He puts himself in danger, but he probably doesn't change the outcome.

"powerlessness, despair, " "lowliness, " "vulnerability, " "marginalized groups, " "forgotten people, " similar statements are repeated in people's interviews with people living with HIV. "It's not going to be easy to fix in the short term because it's a systemic problem. Cut off traffic, cut off logistics, and there is not a good coping mechanism, all aspects of the problem, but for a certain group of people, the problem is more prominent. "Wong said.

One volunteer told people that the requests for assistance they are hearing from young people with college degrees who are used to social networking could be just the tip of the iceberg. The middle-aged and elderly groups, migrant workers with a lower level of education, "do not know how to voice. ".

In the reporter before the deadline of the last moment, Liu Quan has sent news, things suddenly have a turnaround. He didn't see it coming. On the night of the two-day withdrawal, his father, a doctor at the B City hospital, told him that the disease in B city was serious and that the hospital had sent an ambulance to take the medical staff back to work. He seized the opportunity to say that he wanted to visit his mother in county a, and asked his father to take him with him. So, in the ambulance, he made it through the checkpoint.
